&lt;p&gt;In the article &ldquo;The Little Things That Run the World&rdquo; by Edward O. Wilson, I was thrilled to learn about the invertebrates and how such small things can make such a large impact. I thought it was really interesting to learn that invertebrates catch your eye. I was glad to see that common misconceptions about invertebrates were cleared up, and that the author included a conservation moment. Although some invertebrates disrupt ecosystems, humanity and the majority of ecosystems heavily rely on invertebrates. Reading this article gave me a new sense of appreciation. In the other article &ldquo;The Big Things That Run the World&rdquo;, I learned that larger species are harder to study due to their size and low densities, making them more understudied than invertebrates.&nbsp; I also learned that these &ldquo;big things&rdquo; bring stability and maintenance to ecosystems through indirect effects. Overall, I think that both the &ldquo;big&rdquo; and the &ldquo;little&rdquo; things that inhabit this earth are crucial to maintaining balance and stability. More research should definitely be conducted on these matters.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The article, &quot;The Little Things That Run the World,&quot; by Edward O. Wilson, highlights the importance of invertebrates in maintaining ecosystems, challenging the common perception that larger vertebrates dominate environmental processes. I think this is true because without small invertebrates taking care of the ecosystem, there wouldn&#039;t be a livable environment for large vertebrates. Wilson then explores the diversity and abundance of invertebrates, emphasizing their role in the nutrient cycle, decomposition, and ecological balance. The article states that invertebrates, especially ants and termites, are crucial for the health of tropical forests and other habitats. Wilson advocates for increased conservation efforts focused on invertebrates, recognizing their vulnerability to human activities. This is also true because humans are known for destroying habitats for economical-benefit or self-benefit. I think it&#039;s good that he&#039;s spreading knowledge about this, urging for less destructive practices to these habitats.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;On the other hand, the &quot;Big Things That Run the World&quot; article by John Terborgh, provides a counterpoint, emphasizing the ecological importance of larger vertebrates such as jaguars, pumas, and elephants. Terborgh argues that these &quot;big things&quot; play a pivotal role in shaping ecosystems through predation and indirect effects on plant populations. I think this is the more reasonable and better article. While smaller invertebrates provide stability in the environment, larger vertebrates impact ecosystem balance among the food chain. This idea is exactly what we&#039;re currently learning with the S3 Community Dynamics. Large species are vital for an ecosystem equilibrium. Without predators keeping the ecosystem in check, everything would collapse. Terborgh&nbsp;then explains that the absence of top predators can lead to cascading effects, impacting the abundance of smaller vertebrates and even influencing tree species composition. Thus, making top predators the most important, impactful, species in the environment.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;These two articles are basically discussing &quot;bottom-up&quot; and &quot;top-down&quot; effects. The first article discusses the importance of small invertebrates and how they maintain nutrients in the soil, which is the &quot;bottom-up&quot; effect. The second article discusses the importance of top predators and how their absence would lead to cascading effects, impacting the abundance of smaller vertebrates and even tree species composition, which is the &quot;top-down&quot; effect.&nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In &quot;The Little Things that Run the World,&quot; E.O. Wilson emphasizes invertebrates&#039; environmental importance. I loved Wilson&#039;s &quot;new emphasis should be placed on the conservation of invertebrates.&quot; The story piqued my attention in the intricate network of insects with sophisticated ecosystems that sustain our world.&lt;br /&gt;
In &quot;The Big Thing that Run the World,&quot; John Terborgh highlights &quot;big things&quot; and top-down animal management. He says top predators maintain plant and animal variety. Lower predators are indirectly affected by apex predators.&nbsp;In a study where&nbsp;top carnivores were eliminated, predators below them increased dramatically. Higher tropic levels influence their structure and function by preying on lower trophic levels. I agree with Terbough that eliminating top predators would have a greater effect than removing invertebrates.&nbsp;&lt;br /&gt;
&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Hi Juliane,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I&nbsp; agree with you. I think&nbsp;&nbsp;that in the natural world, &quot;the big things&quot; and &quot;the little&nbsp;things&quot; are equally important. Although in particular ecosystems one may be more significant than the other, they are all interdependent, and&nbsp; play&nbsp;a vital function in the ecosystems. I think both should be&nbsp; very valuable for&nbsp;scientific research.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the first article, &quot;The little things that run the world&quot; it discussed how important it is to remember the bugs and small things that we may not be able to see. They have a huge impact on our world and just because we can&#039;t see their effect directly, we can&#039;t forget about them, or disregard them as important beings to how our world functions. It&#039;s&nbsp;interesting to think about these seemingly insignificant creatures as being so vital to our survival and as substantial part of our globe, being 90% of all biomass. I have been learning a lot about ants recently (don&#039;t ask) and through that I have realized just how incredible these little creatures are. They can carry 100x their weight and form complex colonies and structures. they can use tools and even farm! Leaf cutter ants don&#039;t actually eat the leaves like I thought but instead they take the leaves back to their colony and use it to farm a fungus that grows on decaying leaves and then they eat that! I think this article just goes to show that there&#039;s a lot more to tiny things than we realize.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the second article, &quot;The big things that run the world&quot;, Terborgh takes a different perspective. He says the bigger organisms are the ones that have the biggest impact on the ecosystem. He argues that removing the bigger organisms will have a greater impact on an ecosystem because without them, all of the trophic levels below them will be all out of balance. This reminds me of the wolves in Yellowstone that we learned about. When farmers removed the wolves because they were a pest to their sheep, the elk were able to roam freely and eat all the aspen, disrupting the birds and other creatures that lived in the aspen forests. Without the wolves there to control the elk population, the whole ecosystem was out of balance. This supports Terborgh&#039;s argument.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think both articles bring up good points about balance in an ecosystem. In my opinion, the most logical conclusion is that both are correct in some respect. I think all organisms fill a role in an ecosystem so removing any one organism is going to have an effect. All organisms are equally important to sustaining an ecosystem.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The first article, &quot;The Little Things that Run the World,&quot; explores the significance of invertebrates and how they unintentionally stop predatory animals from going extinct. According to the author, if humans were to vanish from the world, invertebrates would not notice, but without invertebrates, humans would probably go extinct. The fact that invertebrates support life at higher trophic levels and that our species would not survive without them fascinates me.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;Big Things That Run the World&quot; highlights the significance of larger animals&nbsp;for the environment.&nbsp;Larger vertebrates affect the equilibrium of the ecosystem across the food chain, whereas smaller invertebrates maintain environmental stability. Big species are essential to the balance of an ecosystem. Everything would collapse if there were no predators to maintain the balance of the ecosystem. A lack of apex predators can have a domino effect on the quantity of lower vertebrates and even the species makeup of trees. Big&nbsp;predators are therefore the most significant and influential creatures in the environment.&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Exploring &quot;The Little Things That Run the World&quot; was eye-opening. I was fascinated by how many invertebrates there are and why they matter so much. Learning about ongoing efforts to protect these species was reassuring. It turns out, we rely heavily on these little creatures for various reasons. Nicole made a great point about their value to biological systems, which I totally agree with.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&quot;The Big Things that Run the World&quot; surprised me by revealing that larger species get less attention from ecologists. This contradicts the idea that all animals are equally important. The lack of research on the connections between big and small species is disappointing. I share Nicole&#039;s hope for future studies in this area.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Lucia&#039;s observation about society&#039;s focus on larger organisms resonates with my own thoughts. It&#039;s interesting to realize the vital role invertebrates play in environmental and human stability. I agree with her that we tend to overlook these &quot;little&quot; species. Emma&#039;s point about the need to conserve creatures we can&#039;t easily see echoes my concerns. It&#039;s essential to shed light on our heavy reliance on these small creatures.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In conclusion. these discussions made me appreciate the importance of both big and little species. There&#039;s a call for more attention to invertebrates, and I join in hoping for future research to explore the relationships between big and small species in ecological communities.&lt;/p&gt;
